President Biden delivered a speech at the Greenwood Cultural Center in Tulsa, Oklahoma, commemorating the 100th anniversary of the Tulsa Race Massacre. He acknowledged the historical significance of the event and recognized the survivors and their descendants. The President emphasized the importance of acknowledging and confronting the truth of the massacre, stating that healing and justice can only come with truth. He also highlighted the ongoing challenges of racial discrimination, including in housing, small business opportunities, education, and voting rights. President Biden called for efforts to combat systemic racism, support Black wealth creation, and protect the right to vote. He also mentioned the need to address hate crimes and domestic terrorism driven by white supremacy. The President expressed optimism for the future, particularly in the younger generation, and called for continued efforts to create a more just and equitable society.